<UserControl x:Class="MIGA.Tool.Windows.UserControls.Setup.InstancesRoot"
             xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
             xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006" 
             xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008" 
             mc:Ignorable="d" 
             d:DesignHeight="205" d:DesignWidth="443" Padding="0">
  <StackPanel Margin="0" Orientation="Vertical">
    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0" Padding="0" HorizontalAlignment="Stretch" VerticalAlignment="Top">
      <Bold>INSTANCES ROOT FOLDER</Bold>             
      <LineBreak />
      The local folder where the <Bold>Sitecore instances were, are and will be installed to</Bold>.
    </TextBlock>
    <Grid HorizontalAlignment="Stretch" Margin="0 4 0 4">
      <Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
        <ColumnDefinition />
        <ColumnDefinition Width="24" />
      </Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
      <TextBox Name="MainRootFolder" HorizontalAlignment="Stretch" Margin="0 0 4 0" />
      <Button Grid.Column="1" Content="..." Name="PickInstancesFolderButton" Click="PickInstancesFolder" />
    </Grid>
    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0" Padding="0" HorizontalAlignment="Stretch" VerticalAlignment="Top">
      While every startup MIGA will retrieve the list of all IIS websites and will try to detect Sitecore instances located within this folder among them. 
      <LineBreak />
      <LineBreak />
      The detection rule is very simple - all Sitecore instances must contain Sitecore.Kernel.dll file in the bin folder, all the rest websites will be ignored.
      <LineBreak />
      <LineBreak />
      <Bold>Tip:</Bold> you can rename Sitecore.Kernel.dll file of the instance you would like to hide from MIGA's sight.
    </TextBlock>
  </StackPanel>
</UserControl>
